1Ô∏è‚É£ ROLE (Namespace-Level Permission)
This Role allows reading Pods only inside default namespace.

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: Role
metadata:
  name: pod-reader
  namespace: default
rules:
- apiGroups: [""]
  resources: ["pods"]
  verbs: ["get", "list", "watch"]

2Ô∏è‚É£ ROLEBINDING (Attach Role to User)
This binds the above Role to a user named dev-user.

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: pod-reader-binding
  namespace: default
subjects:
- kind: User
  name: dev-user
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: pod-reader
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

üü† What This Means
dev-user can: kubectl get pods -n default
But CANNOT: kubectl get pods -n kube-system
Because Role works only in one namespace.

3Ô∏è‚É£ CLUSTERROLE (Cluster-Level Permission)
This ClusterRole allows reading Nodes (cluster-scoped resource).

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRole
metadata:
  name: node-reader
rules:
- apiGroups: [""]
  resources: ["nodes"]
  verbs: ["get", "list"]

4Ô∏è‚É£ CLUSTERROLEBINDING (Attach ClusterRole to User)
This grants cluster-wide access to ops-user.

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRoleBinding
metadata:
  name: node-reader-binding
subjects:
- kind: User
  name: ops-user
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: node-reader
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

üü† What This Means
ops-user can run: kubectl get nodes
From anywhere. 
Because: Nodes are cluster-scoped.

üü† Final Simple Comparison
| Resource           | Scope                              |
| ------------------ | ---------------------------------- |
| Role               | One namespace                      |
| RoleBinding        | Grants Role inside that namespace  |
| ClusterRole        | Cluster-wide permission definition |
| ClusterRoleBinding | Grants cluster-wide access         |



